Introduction to Neural Networks: Bank Churn prediction¶

github link for Jupyter Notebook

Problem Statement¶

In the competitive landscape of banking and financial services, customer retention emerges as a critical challenge, encapsulated by the phenomenon of 'Customer Churn'—the departure of clients to rival institutions. Understanding the myriad factors that drive a customer's decision to leave is crucial for strategic service enhancement. This knowledge enables management to focus their efforts on targeted improvements, prioritizing elements of the service that most significantly impact customer loyalty and decision-making. Addressing this issue not only requires identifying these key factors but also developing actionable strategies that can mitigate churn, thereby ensuring sustained customer engagement and loyalty.

Context¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Customer Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

You as a Data scientist with the bank need to build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether a customer will leave the bank or not in the next 6 months.

Data Dictionary:¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer

  • Surname: Last name of the customer

  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.

  • Geography: A customer’s location

  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer

  • Age: Age of the customer

  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank

  • NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.

  • Balance: Account balance

  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer has credit card or not.

  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary

  • isActiveMember: Is is a categorical variable which decides whether the customer is active member of the bank or not ( Active member in the sense, using bank products regularly, making transactions etc )

  • Exited : whether or not the customer left the bank within six month. It can take two values 0=No ( Customer did not leave the bank ) 1=Yes ( Customer left the bank )

Insights from describe of dataset

Credit Score:

The average credit score among customers is 650.53 with a standard deviation of 96.65, ranging from 350 to 850. This indicates a wide range of creditworthiness among the customers, with most scores clustered around the mean.

Age:

The average age is approximately 39 years, with a standard deviation of 10.49, indicating a middle-aged customer base. The age range is 18 to 92 years, showing diversity in customer demographics.

Tenure:

On average, customers have been with the institution for 5 years, with tenures ranging from 0 to 10 years. This suggests a mix of new and long-term customers.

Balance:

The average account balance is roughly 76,485.89, with a large standard deviation of 62,397.41, indicating significant variability in customer balances. Notably, 25% of customers have a zero balance, which could imply either new accounts or inactive ones.

NumOfProducts:

Customers hold an average of 1.53 products from the institution, with the number of products ranging from 1 to 4. This suggests most customers use a limited range of the institution's offerings.

HasCrCard:

70.55% of customers have a credit card issued by the institution, indicating a high penetration of the institution's credit card among its customers.

IsActiveMember:

51.51% of the customers are marked as active, highlighting that slightly more than half of the customer base is engaged with the institution's products or services.

EstimatedSalary:

The average estimated salary of customers is around 100,090.20, with a broad range (min 11.58 to max 199,992.48), suggesting a wide spectrum of income levels among the customer base.

Exited (Customer Churn):

20.37% of customers have exited, indicating a churn rate that the institution may want to investigate further to understand and potentially reduce.

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

### Function to plot distributions

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

we will primarily consider the R-squared (R2) value as a primary metric, as it indicates the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable(s). A higher R2 value generally indicates a better fit for the model to the data. However, in cases where R2 is not applicable or provides extreme values (especially negative values far from 0), we might consider other metrics like Mean Squared Error (MSE) and the context of the loss values to guide the ranking.

def build_model_SGD():
  ## Initializing the ANN
  model = Sequential()
  input_layer = Dense(16, input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],),activation='relu')
  model.add(input_layer)
  hidden_layer = Dense(8, activation='relu');
  model.add(hidden_layer)
  output_layer = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
  model.add(output_layer)

  # Defining the optimizer
  optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.SGD(0.001)  # Defining the optimizer
  # Compiling the model
  model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
              optimizer=optimizer,
              metrics=['mse'])  # Defining the loss function, optimizer and metrices

  return model

def build_model_adam_and_dropout():
  # Initializing the model
  model_adam_dropout = Sequential()
  model_adam_dropout.add(Dense(16, input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))
  # Adding Dropout with 10%
  model_adam_dropout.add(Dropout(0.2))
  model_adam_dropout.add(Dense(8, input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_uniform'))
  # Adding the output layer with one neuron and linear as activation
  model_adam_dropout.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

  optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(0.001)
  model_adam_dropout.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['mse'])

  return model_adam_dropout

# Adjust the model-building function to accept hyperparameters
def build_model(learning_rate=0.001):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(18, input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],), activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(8, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['mse'])
    return model

# Function for hyperparameter tuning
def model_grid_search(X_train, y_train, fit_params=None):
    model = KerasRegressor(model=build_model, verbose=0)
    param_grid = {
        'model__learning_rate': [0.01, 0.001],
        'epochs': [4, 6],  # Reduced for demonstration
        'batch_size': [128, 256]
    }
    grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid, n_jobs=-1, cv=3)
    #grid_result = grid.fit(X_train, y_train, **(fit_params if fit_params else {}))
    grid_result = grid.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2)
    return grid_result

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

What recommedations would you suggest to the bank?

Customer Retention Efforts:

Focus on the 20.37% churn rate by identifying common factors among those who have exited. Special attention could be given to age, balance, and the number of products held.

Product Engagement:

With an average of 1.53 products per customer, there may be opportunities to cross-sell or upsell, particularly to those with fewer products and high account balances.

Credit Card Penetration:

Given that 70.55% of customers have a credit card, further analysis could reveal opportunities to increase credit card adoption among the remaining customers.

Engagement Strategies:

With just over half of the customers marked as active, targeted marketing campaigns or incentive programs could be used to increase engagement among less active customers.

Service Improvement:

Investigating the reasons behind customer churn, especially among older or long-tenured customers, could provide insights into potential service improvements or product offerings.

Financial Health Programs:

Considering the wide range in customer balances and salaries, personalized financial advice or product offerings tailored to different segments of the customer base could enhance satisfaction and retention.
